this is already supported by passing in druid.indexer.runner.javaOpts in task context.

{
"type" : "index"
"tuningConfig"  : {...}
 "context" : {
        "druid.indexer.runner.javaOpts" : "-server -Xmx256m"
 }
}
Its still undocumented I think, its probably worth adding docs for it if the community finds it useful.

@drcrallen I totally agree with your point. We should use it very carefully not to make a mess. But, I believe there are still some useful usecases though. 

Here is my usecase. I want to attach my debugger to an IndexTask which is forked from a overlord or middle manager. However, IndexTasks often finish its job and the jvm terminates too quickly to attach my debugger to it. So I want to put off the execution of IndexTask until my debugger has got a connection to the forked jvm. Giving `suspend=y` as a jvm option of a child process works out this issue as it delays the execution of code and makes the main thread(I guess) wait for a debugger attachment. But, if I set this option in the overlord configurations, all the tasks forked from the overlord will be stuck waiting for the debugger attachment, which is not the situation I want.

```
"context": {
    "druid.indexer.runner.javaOpts" : "-server -Xmx4g -Xms4g -server -Xdebug -Xrunjdwp:transport=dt_socket,address=0.0.0.0:0,suspend=y"
  }
```

@xvrl this PR should totally use the new proposed abstractions for discovery.
main use case that drove this PR was for re-indexing proposed in #1998 to be able to get aggregators from segment metadata query and coordinator would need to know of brokers(or router) to be able to send the query.
since all realtime ingestion work is being postponed to 0.9.1, so we can sleep on it for now.

other comments

```
@drcrallen : There should be a configuration in jetty to increase the allowed header size as well. Currently there's not a great way to configure jetty options within Druid though.

@xvrl : while there is theoretically no limit to http header sizes, I am worried increasing the header size could cause interoperability issues with browsers, proxies, or other http clients querying Druid. Most of those set limits on the size of http headers, which the user may not have much control over.

@cheddar: Fwiw, I think that the "solution" Druid implements for (1) can be as simple "if the content of the query ocntext map is greater than 2kb, log it and replace it with a UUID that can be used to find the log"
```
